        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested sensitivity: 
As discussed in the Science Justification, we have performed
detailed simulations with different possible models. The results of the
simulations are shown in Fig.4. In order to discriminate between different
families of torus models we need to map the continuum in band 7 down to at
least the second positive contours (0.21 mJy/beam) in Fig.4 with a 
sensitivity of at least 4 sigma, implying a sensitivity of 0.05 mJy per beam.

Imaging requirements: 
As discussed in the Scientific Justification, and as made clear by
the simulations in Fig.4, to distinguish between different torus scenarios
in NGC~1068 (i.e. extended torus in the bulge potential vs compact torus
within the BH gravitational potential) we need an angular resolution of about
0.15" in band 7, which can be achieved with the configuration C34-7 at 353~GHz.

The brightness of the unresolved
bright central source is 15 mJy. Therefore, we will need a dynamic range in the final image 
of 300. This will be straightforward to achieve using self-calibration on the 
bright central source, based on the online CASA guide:
http://casaguides.nrao.edu/index.php?title=TWHydraBand7_Imaging_4.1
that shows Band 7 imaging of TW Hydra with self-calibration, reaching a 
dynamic range of 770.

Correlator setup: 
We have selected the frequency around 353 GHz because at this frequency
the sensitivity (within band 7) is relatively good and it also allows us,
for free, to map also the HCN(4-3) transition. Since our primary goal is to
detect and resolve the continuum emission, we have selected the lowest
resolution and widest possible bandwidth. Both polarizations will be tuned to
the same frequencies.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
